whmurray@aol.com (WHMurray) writes:

>In article <16FEC11F67S86.C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu>,
>C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu writes:

>>   I agree in principle, but in practice, how do you know ahead of time
>>that there will never be a time when this data is *really* important to
>>keep secure? 

>In the general case, I admit that I cannot know.  However, in practice, I
>do know.  For example, my directions to a trader are not sensitive after
>the trade is executed.  Very little data has a life measured in months or
>years.  The classic exceptions appear in international espionage and
>relate to "protecting sources."

>Modern exceptions occur primarily in key management.  Even these yield to
>modern management approaches.


Your directions to a trader may not be sensitive standing alone, but all such
trades taken together can expose your trading method -- and that can be a 
trade secret of your.  (Parallel:  American Airlines is bitching because
Northwest Airlines is hiring away people...people who know how American
deals with bookings forcasts and how to fill planes effectively.)

When in doubt, don't allow disclosure.
